column1: Title: MALT90 Kinematic Distances to Dense Molecular Clumps
Authors: Whitaker J.S., Jackson J.M., Rathborne J.M., Foster J.B.,
Contreras Y., Sanhueza P., Stephens I.W., Longmore S.N.
Table: Results of the kinematic distance analysis
62- 67 F6.2   kpc     Kdt   Kinematic distance to tangent point
68- 73 F6.2   kpc     Kdn   Near kinematic distance
74- 79 F6.2   kpc   b_Kdn   Lower boundary range to Kdn
80- 85 F6.2   kpc   B_Kdn   Upper boundary range to Kdn
86- 91 F6.2   kpc     Kdf   Far kinematic distance
92- 97 F6.2   kpc   b_Kdf   Lower boundary range to Kdf
98-103 F6.2   kpc   B_Kdf   Upper boundary range to Kdf
104-109 F6.2   ---     PHISA Probability of a HISA absoprtion dip
110-118 F9.2   km/s    Mabsv Minimum velocity of significant absorption
123-127 A5     ---     Dflag Kinematic distance ambiguity resolution flag (1)
128-131 I4     ---     Dqual Integer flag for near/far ambiguity resolution (2)
132-138 F7.2   kpc     Dbest Best guess for kinematic distance
139-145 F7.2   kpc   b_Dbest Lower boundary range to Dbest
146-152 F7.2   kpc   B_Dbest Upper boundary range to Dbest
-1 and IM = off-sign velocity that is impossible in this rotation model.
1 and FO = velocity is off-sign but possible in rotation model
2 and BT = velocity is beyond tangent velocity
Note (2): From 0 to 9 where a larger value indicating higher confidence in the
reliability of the near/far distance resolution. We consider the
ambiguity resolution for sources with dqual less than 4 to be dubious.
